strategy:
For the random box tasks, I asked myself "Would I be willing to lose x amount if it meant I had y possibility of gaining z amount?" This is an easy question for many examples such as 10% chance to lose $0 for a 90% chance to gain $25 vs a 100% chance to gain $5. Even with the uncertainty, the distance between $5 and $25 is enough to make me roll the dice. I repeated this evaluation with each version and when it reached a point that I felt the distance between the two values was not enough to justify the uncertainty, I chose the other option (usually %100 chance for gain or loss).

For the average questions, you're simply weighing a gain or loss of x amount against a gain or loss of y amount, except the x and y values are obfuscated through fact that the average values are not presented explicitly. Some I was able to work out the average easily and chose to gain or lose x amount where x > y if a gain or x < y if a loss. However, for the majority of the problems, I was not able to work the average out quickly or efficently, so I guessed on a "gut" feeling of which average would be the best to choose in the given problem.
comments: Unless this level of obfuscation is pertinent to what the survey is measuring, I wish the average values would be displayed for that problem set. No one wants to sit and calculate dozens of averages for a problem set of unknown size.

strategy: The strategy was the same.

It's extremely easy to make the best decision on the average box tasks: you just need to find out the point where the averages of Set B become higher than Set A. There's a totally correct answer every time. 

The random boxes task is a little bit more subjective. I COULD set about calculating expected gain/loss for each row using probability, but doesn't really take into account the fact that I'm completing these surveys because I'm short on money, and in the end, I'd rather have a higher chance of walking away with a reasonable amount of money, even that means I've technically robbed myself of the best odds of walking away with the most money. 
For example:

If I start with $30, Set A has 100 of the same box, and Set B has a 50% chance of losing $25, or losing nothing, then in theory, the expected loss on Set B is $12.50, so I should prefer Set B as soon as Set A dips below -$12. 
But... There's a decent chance with every row of Set B that I walk away with only $5, which is hardly anything - it's not even enough to buy me a pack of cigarettes. Where as, I can go all the way down to -$20 in Set A and know I'm walking away with at least $10. I prefer the lower risk option that represents. I'd rather know I'm walking away with at least a small but meaningful amount of money than maximize my theoretical earnings odds. After all, in the end, I only get one shot.
